<ul class="clean-list list-spaced--more"><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Q&amp;A</li></ul><h4><a href="https://carnegie.ru/2019/11/19/how-cozy-is-russia-and-china-s-military-relationship-pub-80363">How Cozy Is Russia and China’s Military Relationship?</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="https://carnegie.ru/experts/287">Dmitri Trenin</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">November 19, 2019</span></li></ul><p>Russia and China’s strategic military cooperation is becoming ever closer. President Putin has announced that Russia is helping China build an early warning system to spot intercontinental ballistic missile launches.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Op-Ed</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/11/13/in-asia-disruptive-technonationalism-returns-pub-80331">In Asia, Disruptive Technonationalism Returns</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/719">Evan A. Feigenbaum</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">November 13, 2019</span></li></ul><p>Technonationalists, whatever their nationality, take a strategic view of industry and technology. They view it as fundamental to national security and economic competitiveness and take on faith that economic policies must have strategic underpinnings.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Op-Ed</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/11/05/macron-should-carry-flag-for-europe-s-values-to-china-pub-80264">Macron Should Carry the Flag for Europe’s Values to China</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/1408">Philippe Le Corre</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">November 05, 2019</span></li><li><em>Nikkei Asian Review</em></li></ul><p>Macron ought to use his meetings with his Chinese counterpart and other top officials to boldly advance a broader European agenda on issues ranging from climate change to intellectual property and even to human rights.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Strategic Europe</li></ul><h4><a href="https://carnegieeurope.eu/strategiceurope/80242">Macron Goes to China: For Europe or for France?</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/1408">Philippe Le Corre</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 31, 2019</span></li></ul><p>France and Germany must stand united if Europe is to exert any meaningful political and economic influence in its relations with Beijing. But for now, national interests prevail.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> TV/Radio Broadcast</li></ul><h4><a href="https://millercenter.org/security-competition">China: Where Things Stand</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/719">Evan A. Feigenbaum</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 24, 2019</span></li><li>University of Virginia</li></ul><p>What is the long-term future of the U.S.-China relationship?</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Event</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/10/23/moving-target-china-policy-coordination-for-united-states-and-japan-event-7206">Moving Target: China Policy Coordination for the United States and Japan</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="http://www.nda.ac.jp/cc/gsss/faculty/kamiya.html">Matake Kamiya</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.u-tokyo.ac.jp/focus/en/people/people002070.html">Shin Kawashima</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://sais.jhu.edu/faculty/carla-freeman">Carla P. Freeman</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/experts/745">James L. Schoff</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 23, 2019</span></li><li>Washington, DC </li></ul><p>While the United States and Japan share perceptions toward an increasingly assertive China, U.S.-Japan policy coordination vis-à-vis China is under strain.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Op-Ed</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/10/22/antitrust-threat-to-national-security-pub-80404">The Antitrust Threat to National Security</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/1694">Jon Bateman</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 22, 2019</span></li><li><em>Wall Street Journal</em></li></ul><p>The breakup campaign has spawned dozens of antitrust probes against Amazon, Apple, and Google as well as Facebook, and it has started a long-overdue debate about Silicon Valley’s sweeping influence.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Op-Ed</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/10/16/china-s-record-on-intellectual-property-rights-is-getting-better-and-better-pub-80098">China’s Record on Intellectual Property Rights Is Getting Better and Better</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/533">Yukon Huang</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/experts/1721">Jeremy Smith</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 16, 2019</span></li><li><em>Foreign Policy</em></li></ul><p>It is easy to dismiss “acquisition” as a euphemism for theft, but in reality, trade, foreign investment, licensing, imitation,and, yes, theft have all contributed to China’s technological progress. </p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li> Event</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/10/16/can-asia-win-from-u.s.-china-trade-war-event-7203">Can Asia Win from the U.S.-China Trade War?</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/1741">Trinh Nguyen</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/experts/719">Evan A. Feigenbaum</a></li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 16, 2019</span></li><li>Washington, DC </li></ul><p>Trinh Nguyen will discuss the diverse coping strategies of economies outside of China in emerging Asia as they navigate U.S.-China competition and regional and global headwinds.</p></li><li class="clearfix "><ul class="clean-list list-across-divided meta sans-serif uppercase"><li>Alliance policy coordination brief</li></ul><h4><a href="/2019/10/10/competing-with-china-on-technology-and-innovation-pub-80010">Competing With China on Technology and Innovation</a></h4><ul class="meta list-across-divided uppercase sans-serif no-margin-bottom inline-elements"><li><a href="/experts/745">James L. Schoff</a>,&nbsp;Asei Ito</li><li> <span class="inline-block">October 11, 2019</span></li></ul><p>The United States and Japan should collaborate with each other to keep their edge, as China increasingly becomes a competitor in high-tech sectors.</p></li></ul><div class="component align-right"><a href="/regions/all/251?lang=en&amp;pageOn=2" class="button">More</a></div></div></div><div role="tabpanel" id="opinion-tab" class="tab-pane fade"><div id="opinion-panel"></div></div><div role="tabpanel" id="research-tab" class="tab-pane fade"><div id="research-panel"></div></div><div role="tabpanel" id="blogs-tab" class="tab-pane fade"><div id="blogs-panel"></div></div><div role="tabpanel" id="media-tab" class="tab-pane fade"><div id="media-panel"></div></div><div role="tabpanel" id="events-tab" class="tab-pane fade"><div id="events-panel"></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="col col-30 zone-2"><!-- India Elects digital feature--><div class="gutter-bottom"><div class="blog-widget blog-widget--light blog-widget--c